# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1802 United Kingdom general election** was the first general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 5 July 1802 to 28 August 1802, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the new Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Parliament had been composed of members of the former Parliaments of the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Parliament of Great Britain held its last general election in 1796.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The final election for the Parliament of Ireland was held in 1797.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first united Parliament was dissolved on 29 June 1802.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 31 August 1802, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Prime Minister Henry Addington led a war-time administration of pro-government Whigs and Tories, collectively referred to as the "Addingtonians", in office during part of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The previous Prime Minister, William Pitt the Younger, had been out of office since 1801.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] King George III had forced Pitt to resign by refusing to agree to Catholic emancipation (allowing Catholics to sit in Parliament) following the Union.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] His faction in Parliament was generally supportive of the Addington ministry, before becoming increasingly opposed over the course of the Parliamentary term.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] On 25 March 1802 the Treaty of Amiens brought about peace with France, with which Great Britain had been at war since 1792.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The international situation remained uneasy and a renewal of war was still possible.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Treaty was supported by a strong majority of the Commons, only meeting strong opposition from the small group of 'New Opposition' or Grenvillite parliamentarians, formed around Lord Grenville and led in the Commons by William Windham, both former cabinet ministers under Pitt.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] In the election the combination of the followers of Addington and Pitt comfortably defeated both the 'Old' Opposition Foxites under Charles James Fox and the 'New' Opposition of Lord Grenville.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite his reluctance to foster a personal faction and the presence of some of his followers in both support and opposition to Addington, Pitt retained an unclear personal following of around fifty-seven MPs.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a decidedly quiet affair owing to the general popularity of Addington's diplomatic and peace policies.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Two notable results occurred in the urban constituencies of Middlesex and Norwich.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Middlesex the Radical Francis Burdett defeated William Mainwaring, a supporter of Addington.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After an inquiry Burdett was unseated and defeated narrowly at a by-election by Mainwaring's son, George Boulton Mainwaring.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Norwich Windham and fellow conservative incumbent John Frere were defeated by Radical William Smith and Foxite Robert Fellowes in a campaign where Windham's opposition to peace had weakened his popularity.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Windham was promptly returned for St Mawes, a pocket borough of Lord Grenville's brother, Lord Buckingham.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At this period there was not one election day.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After receiving a writ (a royal command) for the election to be held, the local returning officer fixed the election timetable for the particular constituency or constituencies he was concerned with.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Polling in seats with contested elections could continue for many days.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election took place over a period of almost two months.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 5 July to 28 August 1802.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Monmouthshire (1 County constituency with 2 MPs and one single member Borough constituency) is included in Wales in these tables.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Sources for this period may include the county in England.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1806 United Kingdom general election** was the second general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 29 October 1806 to 17 December 1806, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place in a situation of considerable uncertainty about the future of British politics, following the sudden death of William Pitt the Younger and the formation of the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 24 October 1806.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 13 December 1806, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament, before its term expired.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Since the previous general election fighting in the Napoleonic Wars with France had resumed in 1803.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Tory Prime Minister Henry Addington had resigned in 1804.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] William Pitt the Younger formed a new coalition of pro-government Whig and Tory politicians to prosecute the war.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The opposition Whigs, led by Charles James Fox, continued to oppose the government.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] They were strengthened by a group of Pitt's former supporters (such as his cousin William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville) who had aligned themselves with Fox in opposition to Addington after 1802 and who did not accompany Pitt and his other friends back to office in 1804.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] When Pitt died on 23 January 1806 a new ministry was formed by Grenville.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] It included Fox and Addington (now ennobled as the 1st Viscount Sidmouth) as well as other leading political figures of the day.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However it did not include George Canning, who had inherited the leadership of Pitt's faction in the House of Commons or the Duke of Portland who led it in the House of Lords.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] This government was known as the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] An attempt was made to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville also tried to strengthen the government, but was unable to persuade the Pittites to join him either as a body or by detaching some leading figures.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister was not prepared to exclude Fox and his friends as the Pittites wanted.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Grenville then decided to hold a general election to strengthen his government.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Talents were in office at the time of this election and continued after it, but the Ministry was weakened by the death of Fox on 13 September 1806.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The election itself was a disappointment.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] In the eighteenth century a government with the King's backing could expect to make substantial gains at an election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However Pitt's financial reforms had weakened the ability of the Treasury to manipulate election results.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord estimated that the Ministry only gained about thirty seats by the 1806 appeal to the country.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 29 October to 17 December 1806.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1807 United Kingdom general election** was the third general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 4 May 1807 to 9 June 1807.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The third United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 April 1807.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 22 June 1807, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1806 election the Ministry of all the Talents, a coalition of the Foxite and Grenvillite Whig and Addingtonite Tory factions, with William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, as Prime Minister continued in office.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] It had attempted to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The faction formerly led by William Pitt the Younger, before his death in January 1806, were the major group in opposition to the Talents' Ministry.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] George Canning in the House of Commons and the Duke of Portland in the House of Lords were at the head of this opposition.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville and his cabinet lost the support of King George III by trying to legislate to permit Roman Catholics to serve as Army and Navy officers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] When ministers refused to give the King written confirmation that they would not raise the Catholic issue again, he decided to find new servants.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The elderly Duke of Portland was asked to form a new ministry in March 1807.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Portland had been the Whig Prime Minister before, in the 1780s, so now he described himself as the Whig Prime Minister of a Tory ministry.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After Pitt's death the younger Pittites increasingly began calling themselves the Tory Party, whether they had previously belonged to the Whig or Tory tradition.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] This was an important stage in the development of a more organised two-party system, which reduced the influence of factions and connections in British politics.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new ministers found it difficult to manage a House of Commons recently elected to support their opponents.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] A month into the new government the King granted a dissolution.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The government policies of opposing Catholic relief and supporting the traditional powers of the King proved popular (at least with the restricted section of the population enfranchised in elections for the unreformed House of Commons).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After the election the government programme was approved by a vote of 350 to 155 in the House of Commons, demonstrating the substantial gains ministers had made in the election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 4 May to 9 June 1807.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1812 United Kingdom general election** was the fourth general election after the Union of Great Britain and Ireland, held from 5 October 1812 to 10 November 1812, taking place at the height of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The fourth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 September 1812, four months after the Earl of Liverpool succeeded to the premiership following the assassination of Spencer Perceval.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 24 November 1812, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1807 election the Pittite Tory ministry, led as prime minister by the Duke of Portland (who still claimed to be a Whig), continued to prosecute the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] At the core of the opposition were the Foxite Whigs, led since the death of Fox in 1806 by Earl Grey (known by the courtesy title of Viscount Howick and a member of the House of Commons from 1806 to 1807).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] However, as Foord observes: "the affairs of the party during most of this period were in a state of uncertainty and confusion".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey was not the commanding leader Fox had been.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] After Grey inherited his peerage and went to the House of Lords in 1807, the party leadership in the House of Commons was extremely weak.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The Grenvillites, associated with the Whig Prime Minister before Portland, William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, were also in opposition but were of less significance than the Foxites.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite this Grenville was recognised as the first Leader of the Opposition in the House of Lords.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A relative of Grey's wife, George Ponsonby, was proposed to Whig MPs by Grey and Grenville as the Whig leader in the House of Commons.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Ponsonby was the first person recognised as the official Leader of *the* Opposition in the House of Commons, as opposed to the leader of *an* opposition faction.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] He proved to be incompetent but could not be persuaded to resign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Until 1812 the Tory faction associated with another former prime minister, Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth, and were also out of office.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The smallest component of the opposition were the Radicals, who were a largely middle-class group of reformers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] They had philosophical differences with the more aristocratic Whigs, but usually ended up voting with them in Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1809 Portland, whose health was failing, resigned.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Tory Prime Minister was Spencer Perceval.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In April 1812 he brought Sidmouth into the cabinet.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A month later, on 11 May 1812, Perceval was assassinated.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The premiership passed to the Earl of Liverpool, who failed to attract Grenville.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] This was a further stage in the development of a two-party system—just about all Tories supported the government and all Whigs opposed it.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election of 1812 returned the Tories to power for another term.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] An example of what happened in the 1812 election was the Irish constituency of Westmeath.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Walker confirms the date of election was 24 October 1812.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Stooks Smith indicates that there were three days of polling, during which time 950 electors came to the hustings and voted.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The polling in the Berkshire election of 1812 went on for 15 days (with 1,992 electors voting).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contests in the general election was 5 October to 10 November 1812.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1818 United Kingdom general election** was the 5th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 17 June 1818 to 18 July 1818.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Whigs gain a few seats, but the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool retained a majority of around 90 seats.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs were divided over their response to growing social unrest and the introduction of the Corn Laws.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The fifth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 10 June 1818.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 4 August 1818, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth Parliament lasted only about a year and a half, as King George III's death on 29 January 1820 triggered a dissolution of Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory leader was the Earl of Liverpool, who had been prime minister since his predecessor's assassination in 1812.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons was Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party had long suffered from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, the Earl Grey was the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The last Whig Prime Minister, the Lord Grenville, had retired from active politics in 1817.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Earl Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, until his death in 1817, was George Ponsonby, Lady Grey's uncle.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] About a year after Ponsonby's death, George Tierney reluctantly became the recognised Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] However, after 1819 he did not carry out the functions of leader although he retained the title.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1820 United Kingdom general election** was held on 6 March 1820 to 14 April 1820, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Triggered by the death of King George III, it produced the first parliament of the reign of his successor, King George IV.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was held shortly after the Radical War in Scotland and the Cato Street Conspiracy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] In this atmosphere, the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool were able to win a substantial majority over the Whigs.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 February 1820.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 21 April 1820, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament before its term expired.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to two general election victories before that of 1820.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party continued to suffer from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, George Tierney, was successful at first after the Whig gains at the 1818 general election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However, on 18 May 1819, Tierney moved a motion in the House of Commons for a committee on the state of the nation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord comments that "this defeat put an effective end to Tierney's leadership".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However he continued to be the nominal leader at the time of the 1820 election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was triggered by the death of King George III.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 6 March and the last contest on 14 April 1820.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1826 United Kingdom general election** was the 7th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 7 June 1826 to 12 July 1826, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool win a landslide victory over the Whigs.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In Ireland, liberal Protestant candidates favouring Catholic emancipation, backed by the Catholic Association, achieved significant gains.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The seventh United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 2 June 1826.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 25 July 1826, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, the Earl of Liverpool remains the most recent prime minister to have won four successive elections.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to three general election victories before that of 1826.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons until 1822, when he committed suicide, was Robert Stewart.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] He was known by the courtesy title of Viscount Castlereagh, until he inherited his father's Irish peerage and became the 2nd Marquess of Londonderry in 1821.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Londonderry was replaced as leader by George Canning, who remained Leader of the House of Commons in 1826.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1824 the Earl Grey gave up the formal Whig leadership in the Lords, although he remained the most prominent Whig peer.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey asked his friends to look to the leadership of the Marquess of Lansdowne.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Although Lansdowne performed the functions of leader, he did not accept the title.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, Grey was still the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that he would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons at the previous general election, George Tierney, disclaimed the leadership on 23 January 1821.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] No new Whig leader emerged during the rest of the Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] There had been significant developments in Irish politics since the 1820 general election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Whilst Catholics in Ireland—who met the normal property qualifications—had been permitted to vote since before the Union, they were still not eligible to sit in the United Kingdom Parliament.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The right for Catholics to serve in Parliament was known as a measure of Catholic emancipation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1823, Daniel O'Connell started a campaign for repeal of the Act of Union, and took Catholic Emancipation as his rallying call, establishing the Catholic Association.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] From 1826, the Catholic Association began to support pro-emancipation candidates in elections.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Association used its money and manpower to campaign for candidates to be elected into Parliament, to pressure the government from within to pass Catholic emancipation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 7 June and the last contest on 12 July 1826.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1821 the borough of Grampound in Cornwall was disenfranchised for corruption.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Its two seats were transferred to the county of Yorkshire, which from this general election became a four-seat constituency.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The result was a vote in favour of leaving the EU, triggering calls to begin the process of the country's withdrawal from the EU commonly termed "Brexit".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Since 1973, the UK had been a member state of the EU and its predecessor organisation the European Communities (EC) (principally the European Economic Community (EEC), along with other international bodies.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The constitutional implications of membership for the UK became a topic of debate domestically particularly regarding sovereignty.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] A referendum on continued membership of the European Communities (EC) to try to settle the issue was held in 1975, with 67% of voters approving continued membership.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Between 1975 and 2016 as European integration significantly deepened, subsequent EC/EU treaties and agreements were ratified by the UK Parliament but without any public approval.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Following the Conservative Party's victory at the 2015 general election as a main manifesto pledge, the legal basis for the EU referendum was established through the European Union Referendum Act 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Prime Minister David Cameron also oversaw a renegotiation of the terms of EU membership, intending to implement these changes in the event of a Remain result.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The referendum was legally non-binding due to the ancient principle of parliamentary sovereignty, although the government promised to implement the result.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Official campaigning took place between 15 April and 23 June 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The official group for remaining in the EU was Britain Stronger in Europe while Vote Leave was the official group endorsing leaving.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, trade unions, newspapers and prominent individuals were also involved, with both sides having supporters from across the political spectrum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Parties in favour of remaining included Labour, the Liberal Democrats, the Scottish National Party, Plaid Cymru and the Green Party; while the UK Independence Party campaigned in favour of leaving; and the Conservative Party remained neutral.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In spite of the Conservative and Labour Party's official positions, both parties allowed their Members of Parliament to publicly campaign for either side of the issue.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Campaign issues included the costs and benefits of membership for the UK's economy, freedom of movement and migration.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Several allegations of unlawful campaigning and Russian interference arose during and after the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The results recorded 51.9% of the votes cast being in favour of leaving.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Most areas of England and Wales had a majority for Leave, and the majority of voters in Scotland, Northern Ireland, Greater London and Gibraltar chose Remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Voter preference correlated with age, level of education and socioeconomic factors.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The causes and reasoning of the Leave result have been the subject of analysis and commentary.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Immediately after the result, financial markets reacted negatively worldwide, and Cameron announced that he would resign as prime minister and leader of the Conservative Party, which he did in July.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The referendum prompted an array of international reactions.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Jeremy Corbyn faced a Labour Party leadership challenge as a result of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In 2017, the UK gave formal notice of intent to withdraw from the EU, with the withdrawal being formalised in 2020.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The European Communities were formed in the 1950s – the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC) in 1952, and the European Atomic Energy Community (EAEC or Euratom) and European Economic Community (EEC) in 1957.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The EEC, the more ambitious of the three, came to be known as the "Common Market".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The UK first applied to join them in 1961, but this was vetoed by France.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] A later application was successful, and the UK joined in 1973; two years later, a national referendum on continuing EC membership resulted in 67.2% voting "Yes" in favour of continued membership, on a 64.6% national turnout.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] At the May 2012 NATO summit meeting, UK Prime Minister David Cameron, Foreign Secretary William Hague and Ed Llewellyn discussed the idea of using a European Union referendum as a concession to the Eurosceptic wing of the Conservative Party.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On 20 June 2012, a three-clause private member's bill was introduced into the House of Commons by the then Eurosceptic MP Douglas Carswell to end the United Kingdom's EU membership and repeal the European Communities Act 1972, but without containing any commitment to the holding of any referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] It received a second reading in a half-hour long debate in the chamber on 26 October 2012, but did not progress any further.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The draft Bill stated that the referendum had to be held no later than 31 December 2017.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The draft legislation was taken forward as a Private member's bill by Conservative MP James Wharton which was known as the European Union (Referendum) Bill 2013.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The bill's First Reading in the House of Commons took place on 19 June 2013.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Cameron was said by a spokesperson to be "very pleased" and would ensure the Bill was given "the full support of the Conservative Party".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The bill received its Second Reading on 5 July 2013, passing by 304 votes to none after almost all Labour MPs and all Liberal Democrat MPs abstained, cleared the Commons in November 2013, and was then introduced to the House of Lords in December 2013, where members voted to block the bill.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Conservative MP Bob Neill then introduced an Alternative Referendum Bill to the Commons.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] After a debate on 17 October 2014, it passed to the Public Bills Committee, but because the Commons failed to pass a money resolution, the bill was unable to progress further before the dissolution of parliament on 27 March 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] At the European Parliament election in 2014, the UK Independence Party (UKIP) secured more votes and more seats than any other party, the first time a party other than the Conservatives or Labour had topped a nationwide poll in 108 years, leaving the Conservatives in third place.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Under Ed Miliband's leadership between 2010 and 2015, the Labour Party ruled out an in-out referendum unless and until a further transfer of powers from the UK to the EU were to be proposed.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In their manifesto for the 2015 general election, the Liberal Democrats pledged to hold an in-out referendum only in the event of there being a change in the EU treaties.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The UK Independence Party (UKIP), the British National Party (BNP), the Green Party, the Democratic Unionist Party and the Respect Party all supported the principle of a referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In early 2014, David Cameron outlined the changes he aimed to bring about in the EU and in the UK's relationship with it.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] He intended to bring these about during a series of negotiations with other EU leaders and then, if re-elected, to announce a referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In November that year, Cameron gave an update on the negotiations and further details of his aims.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The outcome of the renegotiations was announced in February 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The renegotiated terms were in addition to the United Kingdom's existing opt-outs in the European Union and the UK rebate.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The significance of the changes to the EU-UK agreement was contested and speculated upon, with none of the changes considered fundamental, but some considered important to many British people.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Some limits to in-work benefits for EU immigrants were agreed, but these would apply on a sliding scale for four years and would be for new immigrants only; before they could be applied, a country would have to get permission from the European Council.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Child benefit payments could still be made overseas, but these would be linked to the cost of living in the other country.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On sovereignty, the UK was reassured that it would not be required to participate in "ever closer union"; these reassurances were "in line with existing EU law".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Cameron's demand to allow national parliaments to veto proposed EU laws was modified to allow national parliaments collectively to object to proposed EU laws, in which case the European Council would reconsider the proposal before itself deciding what to do.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On economic governance, anti-discrimination regulations for non-Eurozone members would be reinforced, but they would be unable to veto any legislation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The extent to which the various parts of the agreement would be legally binding is complex; no part of the agreement itself changed EU law, but some parts could be enforceable in international law.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The EU had reportedly offered David Cameron a so-called "emergency brake", which would have allowed the UK to withhold social benefits to new immigrants for the first four years after they arrived; this brake could have been applied for a period of seven years.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] That offer was still on the table at the time of the Brexit referendum, but expired when the vote determined that the UK would leave the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Cameron claimed that "he could have avoided Brexit had European leaders let him control migration", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] However, Angela Merkel said that the offer had not been made by the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Merkel stated in the German Parliament: "If you wish to have free access to the single market then you have to accept the fundamental European rights as well as obligations that come from it.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The planned referendum was included in the Queen's Speech on 27 May 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] It was suggested at the time that Cameron was planning to hold the referendum in October 2016, but the European Union Referendum Act 2015, which authorised it, went before the House of Commons the following day, just three weeks after the election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On the bill's second reading on 9 June, members of the House of Commons voted by 544 to 53 in favour, endorsing the principle of holding a referendum, with only the Scottish National Party voting against.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In contrast to the Labour Party's position prior to the 2015 general election under Miliband, acting Labour leader Harriet Harman committed her party to supporting plans for an EU referendum by 2017, a position maintained by elected leader Jeremy Corbyn.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] To enable the referendum to take place, the European Union Referendum Act was passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] It extended to include and take legislative effect in Gibraltar, and received royal assent on 17 December 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The Act was, in turn, confirmed, enacted and implemented in Gibraltar by the European Union (Referendum) Act 2016 (Gibraltar), which was passed by the Gibraltar Parliament and entered into law upon receiving the assent of the Governor of Gibraltar on 28 January 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The European Union Referendum Act required a referendum to be held on the question of the UK's continued membership of the European Union (EU) before the end of 2017.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] It did not contain any requirement for the UK Government to implement the results of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Instead, it was designed to gauge the electorate's opinion on EU membership.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The referendums held in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland in 1997 and 1998 are examples of this type, where opinion was tested before legislation was introduced.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The UK does not have constitutional provisions which would require the results of a referendum to be implemented, unlike, for example, the Republic of Ireland, where the circumstances in which a binding referendum should be held are set out in its constitution.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In contrast, the legislation that provided for the referendum held on AV in May 2011 would have implemented the new system of voting without further legislation, provided that the boundary changes also provided for in the Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011 were also implemented.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In the event, there was a substantial majority against any change.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The 1975 referendum was held after the re-negotiated terms of the UK's EC membership had been agreed by all EC Member States, and the terms set out in a command paper and agreed by both Houses.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Following the 2016 referendum, the High Court confirmed that the result was not legally binding, owing to the constitutional principles of parliamentary sovereignty and representative democracy, and the legislation authorising the referendum did not contain clear words to the contrary.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Research by the Electoral Commission confirmed that its recommended question "was clear and straightforward for voters, and was the most neutral wording from the range of options ... considered and tested", citing responses to its consultation by a diverse range of consultees.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The proposed question was accepted by the government in September 2015, shortly before the bill's third reading.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Prior to being officially announced, it was widely speculated that a June date for the referendum was a serious possibility.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The First Ministers of Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales co-signed a letter to Cameron on 3 February 2016 asking him not to hold the referendum in June, as devolved elections were scheduled to take place the previous month on 5 May.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] These elections had been postponed for a year to avoid a clash with the 2015 general election, after Westminster had implemented the Fixed-term Parliament Act.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Cameron refused this request, saying people were able to make up their own minds in multiple elections spaced at least six weeks from each other.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On 20 February 2016, Cameron announced that the UK Government would formally recommend to the British people that the UK should remain a member of a reformed European Union and that the referendum would be held on 23 June, marking the official launch of the campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] He also announced that Parliament would enact secondary legislation on 22 February relating to the European Union Referendum Act 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] With the official launch, ministers of the UK Government were then free to campaign on either side of the argument in a rare exception to Cabinet collective responsibility.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Members of the House of Lords, who could not vote in general elections, were able to vote in the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Other than the residents of Gibraltar, British Overseas Territories Citizens residing in the British Overseas Territories were unable to vote in the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Residents of the United Kingdom who were citizens of other EU countries were not allowed to vote unless they were citizens (or were also citizens) of the Republic of Ireland, of Malta, or of the Republic of Cyprus.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The Representation of the People Acts 1983 *(1983 c.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] 50)*, as amended, also permit certain British citizens (but not other British nationals) to vote while resident outside of the United Kingdom, provided they had been living abroad for no more than 15 years.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] A legal challenge to this time limit, brought by British citizens living in Italy and Belgium on the grounds that it interfered with the EU right of free movement, was dismissed by the High Court and on appeal by the Supreme Court.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Voting on the day of the referendum was from 0700 to 2200 BST (WEST) (0700 to 2200 CEST in Gibraltar) in some 41,000 polling stations staffed by over 100,000 poll workers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Each polling station was specified to have no more than 2,500 registered voters.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Under the provisions of the Representation of the People Act 2000, postal ballots were also permitted in the referendum and were sent out to eligible voters some three weeks ahead of the vote (2 June 2016).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The minimum age for voters in the referendum was set to 18 years, in line with the Representation of the People Act, as amended.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] A House of Lords amendment proposing to lower the minimum age to 16 years was rejected.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The deadline to register to vote was initially midnight on 7 June 2016; however, this was extended by 48 hours owing to technical problems with the official registration website on 7 June, caused by unusually high web traffic.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Some supporters of the Leave campaign, including the Conservative MP Sir Gerald Howarth, criticised the government's decision to extend the deadline, alleging it gave Remain an advantage because many late registrants were young people who were considered to be more likely to vote for Remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] According to provisional figures from the Electoral Commission, almost 46.5 million people were eligible to vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Nottingham City Council emailed a Vote Leave supporter to say that the council was unable to check whether the nationality that people stated on their voting registration form was true, and hence that they simply had to assume that the information that was submitted was, indeed, correct.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] 3,462 EU nationals were wrongly sent postal voting cards, due to an IT issue experienced by Xpress, an electoral software supplier to a number of councils.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Xpress was initially unable to confirm the exact number of those affected.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The matter was resolved by the issuance of a software patch which rendered the wrongly recorded electors ineligible to vote on 23 June.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In October 2015, Britain Stronger in Europe, a cross-party group campaigning for Britain to remain a member of the EU, was formed.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] There were two rival groups promoting British withdrawal from the EU that sought to become the official Leave campaign: Leave.EU (which was endorsed by most of UKIP, including Nigel Farage), and Vote Leave (endorsed by Conservative Party Eurosceptics).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In January 2016, Nigel Farage and the Leave.EU campaign became part of the Grassroots Out movement, which was borne out of infighting between Vote Leave and Leave.EU campaigners.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In April, the Electoral Commission announced that Britain Stronger in Europe and Vote Leave were to be designated as the official remain and leave campaigns respectively.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] This gave them the right to spend up to £7,000,000, a free mailshot, TV broadcasts and £600,000 in public funds.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The UK Government's official position was to support the Remain campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] Nevertheless, Cameron announced that Conservative Ministers and MPs were free to campaign in favour of remaining in the EU or leaving it, according to their conscience.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] This decision came after mounting pressure for a free vote for ministers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In an exception to the usual rule of cabinet collective responsibility, Cameron allowed cabinet ministers to campaign publicly for EU withdrawal.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] A Government-backed campaign was launched in April.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] On 16 June, all official national campaigning was suspended until 19 June following the murder of Jo Cox.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] After internal polls suggested that 85% of the UK population wanted more information about the referendum from the government, a leaflet was sent to every household in the UK.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] It contained details about why the government believed the UK should remain in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] This leaflet was criticised by those wanting to leave as giving the remain side an unfair advantage; it was also described as being inaccurate and a waste of taxpayers' money (it cost £9.3m in total).
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] During the campaign, Nigel Farage suggested that there would be public demand for a second referendum should the result be a remain win closer than 52–48%, because the leaflet meant that the remain side had been permitted to spend more money than the leave side.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] In the week beginning on 16 May, the Electoral Commission sent a voting guide regarding the referendum to every household within the UK and Gibraltar to raise awareness of the upcoming referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The eight-page guide contained details on how to vote, as well as a sample of the actual ballot paper, and a whole page each was given to the campaign groups Britain Stronger in Europe and Vote Leave to present their case.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The Vote Leave campaign argued that if the UK left the EU, national sovereignty would be protected, immigration controls could be imposed, and the UK would be able to sign trade deals with the rest of the world.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The UK would also be able to stop membership payments to the EU every week.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p01] The Britain Stronger in Europe campaign argued that leaving the European Union would damage the UK economy, and that the status of the UK as a world influence was hinged upon its membership.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The tables list political parties with representation in the House of Commons or the House of Lords, the European Parliament, the Scottish Parliament, the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Welsh Parliament, or the Gibraltar Parliament at the time of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party (SSP), Left Unity and Mebyon Kernow [Cornwall] supported remaining in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Socialist Party of Great Britain supported neither leave nor remain and the Women's Equality Party had no official position on the issue.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Socialist Equality Party called for an "active boycott" of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Cabinet of the United Kingdom is a body responsible for making decisions on policy and organising governmental departments; it is chaired by the Prime Minister and contains most of the government's ministerial heads.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Following the announcement of the referendum in February, 23 of the 30 Cabinet ministers (including attendees) supported the UK staying in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Iain Duncan Smith, in favour of leaving, resigned on 19 March and was replaced by Stephen Crabb who was in favour of remaining.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Crabb was already a cabinet member, as the Secretary of State for Wales, and his replacement, Alun Cairns, was in favour of remaining, bringing the total number of pro-remain Cabinet members to 25.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Various UK multinationals have stated that they would not like the UK to leave the EU because of the uncertainty it would cause, such as Shell, BT and Vodafone, with some assessing the pros and cons of Britain exiting.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The banking sector was one of the most vocal advocating to stay in the EU, with the British Bankers' Association saying: "Businesses don't like that kind of uncertainty".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] RBS warned of potential damage to the economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Furthermore, HSBC and foreign-based banks JP Morgan and Deutsche Bank claim a Brexit might result in the banks' changing domicile.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] According to Goldman Sachs and the City of London's policy chief, all such factors could impact on the City of London's present status as a European and global market leader in financial services.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In February 2016, leaders of 36 of the FTSE 100 companies, including Shell, BAE Systems, BT and Rio Tinto, officially supported staying in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Moreover, 60% of the Institute of Directors and the EEF memberships supported staying.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Many UK-based businesses, including Sainsbury's, remained steadfastly neutral, concerned that taking sides in the divisive issue could lead to a backlash from customers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Richard Branson stated that he was "very fearful" of the consequences of a UK exit from the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Pointing out that languages, plugs and laws differ between EU member states, Dyson said that the 28-country bloc was not a single market, and argued the fastest growing markets were outside the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Engineering company Rolls-Royce wrote to employees to say that it did not want the UK to leave the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Surveys of large UK businesses showed a strong majority favoured the UK remaining in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Small and medium-sized UK businesses were more evenly split.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Polls of foreign businesses found that around half would be less likely to do business in the UK, while 1% would increase their investment in the UK.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Two large car manufacturers, Ford and BMW, warned in 2013 against Brexit, suggesting it would be "devastating" for the economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Conversely, in 2015, some other manufacturing executives told Reuters that they would not shut their plants if the UK left the EU, although future investment might be put at risk.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The CEO of Vauxhall stated that a Brexit would not materially affect its business.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Foreign-based Toyota CEO Akio Toyoda confirmed that, whether or not Britain left the EU, Toyota would carry on manufacturing cars in Britain as they had done before.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In the week following conclusion of the UK's renegotiation (and especially after Boris Johnson announced that he would support the UK leaving), the pound fell to a seven-year low against the dollar and economists at HSBC warned that it could drop even more.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] At the same time, Daragh Maher, head of HSBC, suggested that if Sterling dropped in value so would the Euro.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] European banking analysts also cited Brexit concerns as the reason for the Euro's decline.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Immediately after a poll in June 2016 showed that the Leave campaign was 10 points ahead, the pound dropped by a further one per cent.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In the same month, it was announced that the value of goods exported from the UK in April had shown a month-on-month increase of 11.2%, "the biggest rise since records started in 1998".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Uncertainty over the referendum result, together with several other factors—US interest rates rising, low commodity prices, low Eurozone growth and concerns over emerging markets such as China—contributed to a high level of stock market volatility in January and February 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On 14 June, polls showing that a Brexit was more likely led to the FTSE 100 falling by 2%, losing £98 billion in value.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] After further polls suggested a move back towards Remain, the pound and the FTSE recovered.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On the day of the referendum, sterling hit a 2016 high of $1.5018 for £1 and the FTSE 100 also climbed to a 2016 high, as a new poll suggested a win for the Remain campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Initial results suggested a vote for 'Remain' and the value of the pound held its value.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] However, when the result for Sunderland was announced, it indicated an unexpected swing to 'Leave'.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Subsequent results appeared to confirm this swing and sterling fell in value to $1.3777, its lowest level since 1985.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On the following Monday when the markets opened, £1 sterling fell to a new low of $1.32.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Furthermore, that over the period from the announcement of the referendum, the exchange rate fluctuated markedly around its trend and one can also identify a larger effect based on the "wrong-footing" of markets at the point when the outcome was announced.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] When the London Stock Exchange opened on the morning of 24 June, the FTSE 100 fell from 6338.10 to 5806.13 in the first ten minutes of trading.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] It recovered to 6091.27 after a further 90 minutes, before further recovering to 6162.97 by the end of the day's trading.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] When the markets reopened the following Monday, the FTSE 100 showed a steady decline losing over 2% by mid-afternoon.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Upon opening later on the Friday after the referendum, the US Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped nearly 450 points or about 2½% in less than half an hour.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Associated Press called the sudden worldwide stock market decline a stock market crash.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Investors in worldwide stock markets lost more than the equivalent of US$2 trillion on 24 June 2016, making it the worst single-day loss in history, in absolute terms.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The market losses amounted to US$3 trillion by 27 June.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Sterling fell to a 31-year low against the US dollar.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The UK's and the EU's sovereign debt credit ratings were also lowered to AA by Standard & Poor's.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] By mid-afternoon on 27 June 2016, sterling was at a 31-year low, having fallen 11% in two trading days, and the FTSE 100 had surrendered £85 billion; however, by 29 June it had recovered all its losses since the markets closed on polling day and the value of the pound had begun to rise.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The referendum was generally well-accepted by the European far right.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Marine Le Pen, the leader of the French *Front national*, described the possibility of a Brexit as "like the fall of the Berlin Wall" and commented that "Brexit would be marvellous – extraordinary – for all European peoples who long for freedom".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A poll in France in April 2016 showed that 59% of the French people were in favour of Britain remaining in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Dutch politician Geert Wilders, leader of the Party for Freedom, said that the Netherlands should follow Britain's example: "Like in the 1940s, once again Britain could help liberate Europe from another totalitarian monster, this time called 'Brussels'.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Polish President Andrzej Duda lent his support for the UK remaining within the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Moldovan Prime Minister Pavel Filip asked all citizens of Moldova living in the UK to speak to their British friends and convince them to vote for the UK to remain in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Spanish foreign minister José García-Margallo said Spain would demand control of Gibraltar the "very next day" after a British withdrawal from the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Margallo also threatened to close the border with Gibraltar if Britain left the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Swedish foreign minister Margot Wallström said on 11 June 2016 that if Britain left the EU, other countries would have referendums on whether to leave the EU, and that if Britain stayed in the EU, other countries would negotiate, ask and demand to have special treatment.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Czech prime minister Bohuslav Sobotka suggested in February 2016 that the Czech Republic would start discussions on leaving the EU if the UK voted for an EU exit.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Christine Lagarde, the managing director of the International Monetary Fund, warned in February 2016 that the uncertainty over the outcome of the referendum would be bad "in and of itself" for the British economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In response, Leave campaigner Priti Patel said a previous warning from the IMF regarding the coalition government's deficit plan for the UK was proven incorrect and that the IMF "were wrong then and are wrong now".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Also in October 2015, the United States Ambassador to the United Kingdom Matthew Barzun said that UK participation in NATO and the EU made each group "better and stronger" and that, while the decision to remain or leave is a choice for the British people, it was in the US interest that it remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In April 2016, eight former US Secretaries of the Treasury, who had served both Democratic and Republican presidents, urged Britain to remain in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In July 2015, President Barack Obama confirmed the long-standing US preference for the UK to remain in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Obama said: "Having the UK in the EU gives us much greater confidence about the strength of the transatlantic union, and is part of the cornerstone of the institutions built following World War II that has made the world safer and more prosperous.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] We want to make sure that the United Kingdom continues to have that influence." Some Conservative MPs accused U.S.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Two years later, one of Obama's former aides recounted that the public intervention was made following a request by Cameron.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Prior to the vote, Republican presidential candidate Donald Trump anticipated that Britain would leave based on its concerns over migration, while Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton hoped that Britain would remain in the EU to strengthen transatlantic co-operation.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Reuters reported in June 2016 that the Chinese government was worried about an EU without Britain being weaker, particularly in its role as a counterbalance to the United States.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In February 2016, the finance ministers from the G20 major economies warned for the UK to leave the EU would lead to "a shock" in the global economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In May 2016, the Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull said that Australia would prefer the UK to remain in the EU, but that it was a matter for the British people, and "whatever judgement they make, the relations between Britain and Australia will be very, very close".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Indonesian president Joko Widodo stated during a European trip that he was not in favour of Brexit.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Sri Lankan Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe issued a statement of reasons why he was "very concerned" at the possibility of Brexit.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Russian President Vladimir Putin said: "I want to say it is none of our business, it is the business of the people of the UK." Maria Zakharova, the official Russian foreign ministry spokesperson, said: "Russia has nothing to do with Brexit.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] We are not involved in this process in any way.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In November 2015, the Governor of the Bank of England Mark Carney said that the Bank of England would do what was necessary to help the UK economy if the British people voted to leave the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In March 2016, Carney told MPs that an EU exit was the "biggest domestic risk" to the UK economy, but that remaining a member also carried risks, related to the European Monetary Union, of which the UK is not a member.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In May 2016, Carney said that a "technical recession" was one of the possible risks of the UK leaving the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] However, Iain Duncan Smith said Carney's comment should be taken with "a pinch of salt", saying "all forecasts in the end are wrong".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In December 2015, the Bank of England published a report about the impact of immigration on wages.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The report concluded that immigration put downward pressure on workers' wages, particularly low-skilled workers: a 10 per cent point rise in the proportion of migrants working in low-skilled services drove down the average wages of low-skilled workers by about 2 per cent.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The 10 percentage point rise cited in the paper is larger than the entire rise observed since the 2004–06 period in the semi/unskilled services sector, which is about 7 percentage points.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In March 2016, Nobel prize-winning economist Joseph Stiglitz argued that he might reconsider his support for the UK remaining in the EU if the proposed Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) were to be agreed to.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Stiglitz warned that under the investor-state dispute settlement provision in current drafts of the TTIP, governments risked being sued for loss of profits resulting from new regulations, including health and safety regulations to limit the use of asbestos or tobacco.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Germany with its 'social market' economy stands midway between the French *dirigiste* economic model and the British free-market economic model.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A study by Oxford Economics for the Law Society of England and Wales has suggested that Brexit would have a particularly large negative impact on the UK financial services industry and the law firms that support it, which could cost the law sector as much as £1.7bn per annum by 2030.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Slowly but surely, these new laws dictated by EU commissars are conquering English common law, imposing upon UK businesses and citizens an ever-growing collection of fastidious regulations in every field".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Thiemo Fetzer, professor of economics from University of Warwick, analysed the welfare reforms in the UK since 2000 and suggests that numerous austerity-induced welfare reforms from 2010 onwards have stopped contributing to mitigate income differences through transfer payments.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] This could be a key activating factor of anti-EU preferences that lie behind the development of economic grievances and the lack of support in a Remain victory.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Instead, they claim that orthodox economic theory has guided poor economic policy such as investment and that has been the cause of problems within the British economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In May 2016, the Institute for Fiscal Studies said that an EU exit could mean two more years of austerity cuts as the government would have to make up for an estimated loss of £20 billion to £40 billion of tax revenue.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The head of the IFS, Paul Johnson, said that the UK "could perfectly reasonably decide that we are willing to pay a bit of a price for leaving the EU and regaining some sovereignty and control over immigration and so on.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A poll of lawyers conducted by a legal recruiter in late May 2016 suggested 57% of lawyers wanted to remain in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] During a Treasury Committee shortly following the vote, economic experts generally agreed that the leave vote would be detrimental to the UK economy.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In particular, eight out of 10 respondents felt that leaving the EU would have a negative impact on trusts' ability to recruit health and social care staff.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In April 2016, a group of nearly 200 health professionals and researchers warned that the NHS would be in jeopardy if Britain left the European Union.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The leave campaign reacted by saying more money would be available to be spent on the NHS if the UK left the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Guidelines by the Charity Commission for England and Wales that forbid political activity for registered charities have limited UK health organizations' commentary on EU poll, according to anonymous sources consulted by the Lancet.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] According to Simon Wessely, head of psychological medicine at the Institute of Psychiatry, King's College London – neither a special revision of the guidelines from 7 March 2016, nor Cameron's encouragement have made health organisations, willing to speak out.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Genetic Alliance UK the Royal College of Midwives the Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry and the Chief Executive of the National Health Service had all stated pro-remain positions by early June 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A June 2016 survey of British fishermen found that 92% intended to vote to leave the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The EU's Common Fisheries Policy was mentioned as a central reason for their near-unanimity.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] More than three-quarters believed that they would be able to land more fish, and 93% stated that leaving the EU would benefit the fishing industry.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In May 2016, more than 300 historians wrote in a joint letter to *The Guardian* that Britain could play a bigger role in the world as part of the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] They said: "As historians of Britain and of Europe, we believe that Britain has had in the past, and will have in the future, an irreplaceable role to play in Europe." On the other hand, many historians argued in favour of leaving, seeing it as a return to self-sovereignty.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Iain Mansfield, a Cambridge graduate and UKTI diplomat, submitted the winning thesis: *A Blueprint for Britain: Openness not Isolation*.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Mansfield's submission focused on addressing both trade and regulatory issues with EU member states as well as other global trading partners.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The largest ever poll (of 20,000 people, in March 2014) showed the public evenly split on the issue, with 41% in favour of withdrawal, 41% in favour of membership, and 18% undecided.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] However, when asked how they would vote if Britain renegotiated the terms of its membership of the EU, and the UK Government stated that British interests had been satisfactorily protected, more than 50% indicated that they would vote for Britain to stay in.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Analysis of polling suggested that young voters tended to support remaining in the EU, whereas those older tend to support leaving, but there was no gender split in attitudes.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In February 2016 YouGov also found that euroscepticism correlated with people of lower income and that "higher social grades are more clearly in favour of remaining in the EU", but noted that euroscepticism also had strongholds in "the more wealthy, Tory shires".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Scotland, Wales and many English urban areas with large student populations were more pro-EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Big business was broadly behind remaining in the EU, though the situation among smaller companies was less clear-cut.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In polls of economists, lawyers, and scientists, clear majorities saw the UK's membership of the EU as beneficial.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On the day of the referendum, the bookmaker Ladbrokes offered odds of 6/1 against the UK leaving the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, spread betting firm Spreadex offered a Leave Vote Share spread of 45–46, a Remain Vote Share spread of 53.5-54.5, and a Remain Binary Index spread of 80–84.7, where victory for Remain would makeup to 100 and a defeat 0.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Shortly after the polls closed at 10 pm on 23 June, the British polling company YouGov released a poll conducted among almost 5,000 people on the day; it suggested a narrow lead for "Remain", which polled 52% with Leave polling 48%.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] It was later criticised for overestimating the margin of the "Remain" vote, when it became clear a few hours later that the UK had voted 51.9% to 48.1% in favour of leaving the European Union.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The number of jobs lost or gained by a withdrawal was a dominant issue; the BBC's outline of issues warned that a precise figure was difficult to find.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Leave campaign argued that a reduction in red tape associated with EU regulations would create more jobs and that small to medium-sized companies who trade domestically would be the biggest beneficiaries.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Those arguing to remain in the EU, claimed that millions of jobs would be lost.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The EU's importance as a trading partner and the outcome of its trade status if it left was a disputed issue.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Whereas those wanting to stay cited that most of the UK's trade was made with the EU, those arguing to leave say that its trade was not as important as it used to be.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Scenarios of the economic outlook for the country if it left the EU were generally negative.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The United Kingdom also paid more into the EU budget than it received.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Citizens of EU countries, including the United Kingdom, have the right to travel, live and work within other EU countries, as free movement is one of the four founding principles of the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Campaigners for remaining said that EU immigration had positive impacts on the UK's economy, citing that the country's growth forecasts were partly based upon continued high levels of net immigration.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Office for Budget Responsibility also claimed that taxes from immigrants boost public funding.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A recent academic paper suggests that migration from Eastern Europe put pressure on wage growth at the lower end of the wage distribution, while at the same time increasing pressures on public services and housing.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Leave campaign believed reduced immigration would ease pressure in public services such as schools and hospitals, as well as giving British workers more jobs and higher wages.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] According to official Office for National Statistics data, net migration in 2015 was 333,000, which was the second highest level on record, far above David Cameron's target of tens of thousands.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The figures also showed that 77,000 EU migrants who came to Britain were looking for work.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Conservative MEP (Member of the European Parliament) representing South East England, Daniel Hannan, predicted on the BBC programme *Newsnight* that the level of immigration would remain high after Brexit.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The possibility that the UK's smaller constituent countries could vote to remain within the EU but find themselves withdrawn from the EU led to discussion about the risk to the unity of the United Kingdom.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Scotland's First Minister, Nicola Sturgeon, made it clear that she believed that a second independence referendum would "almost certainly" be demanded by Scots if the UK voted to leave the EU but Scotland did not.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The First Minister of Wales, Carwyn Jones, said: "If Wales votes to remain in [the EU] but the UK votes to leave, there will be a... constitutional crisis.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The UK cannot possibly continue in its present form if England votes to leave and everyone else votes to stay".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] There was concern that the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP), a proposed trade agreement between the United States and the EU, would be a threat to the public services of EU member states.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Jeremy Corbyn, on the Remain side, said that he pledged to veto TTIP in Government.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] John Mills, on the Leave side, said that the UK could not veto TTIP because trade pacts were decided by Qualified Majority Voting in the European Council.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] There was debate over the extent to which the European Union membership aided security and defence in comparison to the UK's membership of NATO and the United Nations.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Security concerns over the union's free movement policy were raised too, because people with EU passports were unlikely to receive detailed checks at border control.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] A debate was held by *The Guardian* on 15 March 2016, featuring the leader of UKIP Nigel Farage, Conservative MP Andrea Leadsom, the leader of Labour's "yes" campaign Alan Johnson and former leader of the Liberal Democrats Nick Clegg.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Earlier in the campaign, on 11 January, a debate took place between Nigel Farage and Carwyn Jones, who was at the time the First Minister of Wales and leader of the Welsh Labour Party.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Reluctance to have Conservative Party members argue against one another has seen some debates split, with Leave and Remain candidates interviewed separately.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The scheduled debates and question sessions included a number of question and answer sessions with various campaigners. and a debate on ITV held on 9 June that included Angela Eagle, Amber Rudd and Nicola Sturgeon for remain, Boris Johnson, Andrea Leadsom, and Gisela Stuart for leave.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Voting took place from 0700 BST (WEST) until 2200 BST (same hours CEST in Gibraltar) in 41,000 polling stations across 382 voting areas, with each polling station limited to a maximum of 2,500 voters.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The referendum was held across all four countries of the United Kingdom, as well as in Gibraltar, as a single majority vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The 382 voting areas were grouped into twelve regional counts and there was separate declarations for each of the regional counts.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In England, as happened in the 2011 AV referendum, the 326 districts were used as the local voting areas and the returns of these then fed into nine English regional counts.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In Scotland the local voting areas were the 32 local councils which then fed their results into the Scottish national count, and in Wales the 22 local councils were their local voting areas before the results were then fed into the Welsh national count.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Northern Ireland, as was the case in the AV referendum, was a single voting and national count area although local totals by Westminster parliamentary constituency areas were announced.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Gibraltar was a single voting area, but as Gibraltar was to be treated and included as if it were a part of South West England, its results was included together with the South West England regional count.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The following table shows the breakdown of the voting areas and regional counts that were used for the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On 16 June 2016, a pro-EU Labour MP, Jo Cox, was shot and killed in Birstall, West Yorkshire the week before the referendum by a man calling out "death to traitors, freedom for Britain", and a man who intervened was injured.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The two rival official campaigns agreed to suspend their activities as a mark of respect to Cox.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] After the referendum, evidence emerged that Leave.EU had continued to put out advertising the day after Jo Cox's murder.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] David Cameron cancelled a planned rally in Gibraltar supporting British EU membership.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Polling officials in the Yorkshire and Humber region also halted counting of the referendum ballots on the evening of 23 June to observe a minute of silence.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] The Conservative Party, Liberal Democrats, UK Independence Party and the Green Party all announced that they would not contest the ensuing by-election in Cox's constituency as a mark of respect.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On polling day itself two polling stations in Kingston upon Thames were flooded by rain and had to be relocated.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] In advance of polling day, concern had been expressed that the courtesy pencils provided in polling booths could allow votes to be later altered.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] Although this was widely dismissed as a conspiracy theory (see: Voting pencil conspiracy theory), some Leave campaigners advocated that voters should instead use pens to mark their ballot papers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] On polling day in Winchester an emergency call was made to police about "threatening behaviour" outside the polling station.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p02] After questioning a woman who had been offering to lend her pen to voters, the police decided that no offence was being committed.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The final result was announced on Friday 24 June 2016 at 07:20 BST by then-Electoral Commission Chairwoman Jenny Watson at Manchester Town Hall after all 382 voting areas and the twelve UK regions had declared their totals.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] With a national turnout of 72% across the United Kingdom and Gibraltar (representing 33,577,342 people), at least 16,788,672 votes were required to win a majority.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The electorate voted to "Leave the European Union", with a majority of 1,269,501 votes (3.8%) over those who voted "Remain a member of the European Union".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The national turnout of 72% was the highest ever for a UK-wide referendum, and the highest for any national vote since the 1992 general election.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Roughly 38% of the UK population voted to leave the EU and roughly 35% voted to remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] It was described by Theresa May as the "largest democratic exercise in our country's history".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Voting figures from local referendum counts and ward-level data (using local demographic information collected in the 2011 census) suggests that Leave votes were strongly correlated with lower qualifications and higher age.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The data were obtained from about one in nine wards in England and Wales, with very little information from Scotland and none from Northern Ireland.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] A YouGov survey reported similar findings; these are summarised in the charts below.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Researchers based at the University of Warwick found that areas with "deprivation in terms of education, income and employment were more likely to vote Leave".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Leave vote tended to be greater in areas which had lower incomes and high unemployment, a strong tradition of manufacturing employment, and in which the population had fewer qualifications.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] It also tended to be greater where there was a large flow of Eastern European migrants (mainly low-skilled workers) into areas with a large share of native low-skilled workers.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Those in lower social grades (especially the 'working class') were more likely to vote Leave, while those in higher social grades (especially the 'upper middle class') were more likely to vote Remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Polls by Ipsos MORI, YouGov and Lord Ashcroft all assert that 70–75% of under 25s voted 'remain'.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Additionally according to YouGov, only 54% of 25- to 49-year-olds voted 'remain', whilst 60% of 50- to 64-year-olds and 64% of over-65s voted 'leave', meaning that the support for 'remain' was not as strong outside the youngest demographic.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Also, YouGov found that around 87% of under-25s in 2018 would now vote to stay in the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Immigration is thought to be a particular worry for older people that voted Leave, who consider it a potential threat to national identity and culture.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The polling found that the main reasons people had voted Leave were "the principle that decisions about the UK should be taken in the UK", and that leaving "offered the best chance for the UK to regain control over immigration and its own borders".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The main reason people voted Remain was that "the risks of voting to leave the EU looked too great when it came to things like the economy, jobs and prices".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The referendum was criticised for not granting people younger than 18 years of age a vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Unlike in the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, the vote was not extended to 16- and 17-year-old citizens.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Critics argued that these people would live with the consequences of the referendum for longer than those who were able to vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Some supporters for the inclusion of these young citizens considered this exclusion a violation of democratic principles and a major shortcoming of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The foreign ministry of Ireland stated on 24 June 2016 that the number of applications from the UK for Irish passports had increased significantly.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Enquiries about passports also increased: the Irish Embassy in London reported 4,000 a day immediately after the vote to leave, in comparison with the normal 200 a day.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Other EU nations also had increases in requests for passports from British citizens, including France and Belgium.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] There were more than a hundred reports of racist abuse and hate crime in the immediate aftermath of the referendum, with many citing the plan to leave the European Union.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] It was claimed that there had been a 57% increase in hate crime following the referendum vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] However, the National Police Chiefs' Council Lead for Hate Crime, Assistant Chief Constable Mark Hamilton, said: "This should not be read as a national increase in hate crime of 57% but an increase in reporting through one mechanism".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Others claimed that the numbers did not necessarily reflect "any objective spread in modern Britain", but that the apparent spike in hate crime was the result of the subjective definition of the crime and that the police being incentivised "to find hatred".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In the UK, crimes are recorded as hate crimes based on the perception of the victim.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 24 June 2016, a Polish school in Cambridgeshire was vandalised with a sign reading "Leave the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Following the referendum result, similar signs were distributed outside homes and schools in Huntingdon, with some left on the cars of Polish residents collecting their children from school.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 26 June, the London office of the Polish Social and Cultural Association was vandalised with graffiti that was initially characterised as a racist hate crime.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] However it later emerged that the graffiti, which said, 'F*** you OMP' may have been directed at OMP, a eurosceptic Polish think tank that had issued a statement congratulating Britain on its Brexit vote.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] This incident was also unsuccessfully investigated by the police.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In Wales, a Muslim woman was told to leave after the referendum, even though she had been born and raised in the United Kingdom.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Other reports of racism occurred as perceived foreigners were targeted in supermarkets, on buses and on street corners, and told to leave the country immediately.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] All such incidents were widely condemned by politicians and religious leaders.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] By September 2016, it was reported, according to the LGBT anti-violence charity Galop, that attacks on LGBT people in the United Kingdom had risen by 147% in the three months after the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] However some gay commentators dismissed the claim of a link between Brexit and an increase in attacks on members of the LGBTQ community.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The killing of a Polish national Arkadiusz Jozwik in Harlow, Essex in August 2016 was widely, but falsely, speculated to be linked to the Leave result.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] A BBC *Newsnight* report by John Sweeney showed an interview with someone who knew the victim who then claimed that leading Brexit campaigner Nigel Farage had "blood on his hands".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Nigel Farage criticised the "sensationalist" reporting of the issue and complained to the BBC about broadcasting the "blood on his hands" remark.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The petition had actually been initiated by someone favouring an exit from the EU, one William Oliver Healey of the English Democrats on 24 May 2016, when the Remain faction had been leading in the polls, and had received 22 signatures prior to the referendum result being declared.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 26 June, Healey made it clear on his Facebook page that the petition had actually been started to favour an exit from the EU and that he was a strong supporter of the Vote Leave and Grassroots Out campaigns.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Healey also claimed that the petition had been "hijacked by the remain campaign".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] English Democrats chairman Robin Tilbrook suggested those who had signed the petition were experiencing "sour grapes" about the result of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] It attracted more than four million signatures, meaning it was considered for debate in Parliament; this debate took place on 5 September 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 27 June 2016, David Cameron's spokesperson stated that holding another vote on Britain's membership of the European Union was "not remotely on the cards".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Home Secretary Theresa May made the following comment when announcing her candidacy to replace Cameron as Conservative leader (and hence as Prime Minister) on 30 June: "The campaign was fought ... and the public gave their verdict.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] There must be no attempts to remain inside the EU ... and no second referendum. ...
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Brexit means Brexit." The petition was rejected by the government on 9 July.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Its response said that the referendum vote "must be respected" and that the government "must now prepare for the process to exit the EU".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 24 June, the Conservative Party leader and Prime Minister David Cameron announced that he would resign by October because the Leave campaign had been successful in the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The leadership election was scheduled for 9 September.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The new leader would be in place before the autumn conference set to begin on 2 October.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Unexpectedly, Boris Johnson, who had been a leading figure for Vote Leave, declined to be nominated shortly before the deadline for nominations.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 13 July, almost three weeks after the vote, Theresa May succeeded Cameron as Prime Minister.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Labour Party leader Jeremy Corbyn faced growing criticism from his party, which had supported remaining within the EU, for poor campaigning.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 26 June 2016, Corbyn sacked Hilary Benn (the shadow foreign secretary) for apparently leading a coup against him.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] This led to a string of Labour MPs quickly resigning their roles in the party.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] A no confidence motion was held on 28 June; Corbyn lost the motion with more than 80% (172) of MPs voting against him.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Corbyn responded with a statement that the motion had no "constitutional legitimacy" and that he intended to continue as the party's leader.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The vote did not require the party to call a leadership election but after Angela Eagle and Owen Smith launched leadership challenges to Corbyn, the 2016 Labour Party leadership election was triggered.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Corbyn won the contest, with a larger share of the vote than in 2015.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 4 July 2016 Nigel Farage stood down as the leader of UKIP, stating that his "political ambition has been achieved" following the result of the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Following the resignation of the party leader Diane James, Farage became an interim leader on 5 October 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] He was succeeded by Paul Nuttall on 28 November 2016.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon said on 24 June 2016 that it was "clear that the people of Scotland see their future as part of the European Union" and that Scotland had "spoken decisively" with a "strong, unequivocal" vote to remain in the European Union.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On the same day, the Scottish Government announced that officials would plan for a "highly likely" second referendum on independence from the United Kingdom and start preparing legislation to that effect.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Former First Minister Alex Salmond said that the vote was a "significant and material change" in Scotland's position within the United Kingdom, and that he was certain his party would implement its manifesto on holding a second referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In reaction to the lack of a unified pro-EU voice following the referendum, the Liberal Democrats and others discussed the launch of a new centre-left political movement.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] This was officially launched on 24 July 2016 as More United.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On the morning of 24 June, the pound sterling fell to its lowest level against the US dollar since 1985.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The drop over the day was 8% – the biggest one-day fall in the pound since the introduction of floating exchange rates following the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1971.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The FTSE 100 initially fell 8%, then recovered to be 3% down by the close of trading on 24 June.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The FTSE 100 index fully recovered by 29 June and subsequently rose above its pre-referendum levels.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The referendum result also had an immediate impact on some other countries.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The South African rand experienced its largest single-day decline since 2008, dropping over 8% against the United States dollar.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Other countries affected included Canada, whose stock exchange fell 1.70%, Nigeria and Kenya.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] He stated that the bank's models "were rather narrow and fragile [and] ill-equipped to making sense of behaviours that were deeply irrational" and said that his "profession is to some degree in crisis" due to this and the unforeseen 2007–2008 crisis.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In August 2016, the Electoral Reform Society published a highly critical report on the referendum and called for a review of how future events are run.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Contrasting it very unfavourably with the 'well-informed grassroots' campaign for Scottish independence, Katie Ghose described it as "dire" with "glaring democratic deficiencies" which left voters bewildered.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Ghose noted a generally negative response to establishment figures with 29% of voters saying David Cameron made them more likely to vote leave whereas only 14% said he made them want to vote remain.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Looking ahead, the society called for an official organisation to highlight misleading claims and for Office of Communications (Ofcom) to define the role that broadcasters were expected to play.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The BBC, ITV and Sky News all provided live coverage of the counts and the reaction to the result.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The BBC's coverage, presented by David Dimbleby, Laura Kuenssberg and John Curtice, was simulcast domestically on BBC One and the BBC News Channel, and internationally on BBC World News.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] ITV's coverage was presented by Tom Bradby, Robert Peston and Allegra Stratton.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The BBC called the referendum result for Leave with its projected forecast at 04:40 BST on 24 June.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 9 May 2016, Leave.EU was fined £50,000 by the UK Information Commissioner's Office 'for failing to follow the rules about sending marketing messages': they sent people text messages without having first gained their permission to do so.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In February 2017, the Electoral Commission announced that it was investigating the spending of Stronger in and Vote Leave, along with smaller parties, as they had not submitted all the necessary invoices, receipts, or details to back up their accounts.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In April 2017, the Commission specified that 'there were reasonable grounds to suspect that potential offences under the law may have occurred' in relation to Leave.EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 4 March 2017, the Information Commissioner's Office also reported that it was 'conducting a wide assessment of the data-protection risks arising from the use of data analytics, including for political purposes' in relation to the Brexit campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] It was specified that among the organisations to be investigated was Cambridge Analytica and its relationship with the Leave.EU campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In May 2017, *The Irish Times* reported that £425,622 donated by the Constitutional Research Council to the Democratic Unionist Party for spending during the referendum may have originated in Saudi Arabia.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In November 2017, the Electoral Commission said that it was investigating allegations that Arron Banks, an insurance businessman and the largest single financial supporter of Brexit, violated campaign spending laws.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The commission's investigation focuses on both Banks and Better for the Country Limited, a company of which Banks is a director and majority shareholder.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The company donated £2.4 million to groups supporting British withdrawal from the EU.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The investigation began after the Commission found "initial grounds to suspect breaches of electoral law".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In December 2017, the Electoral Commission announced several fines related to breaches of campaign finance rules during the referendum campaign.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Liberal Democrats were fined £18,000 and Open Britain (formerly Britain Stronger in Europe) paid £1,250 in fines.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Electoral Commission's director of political finance and regulation and legal counsel said that the "level of fine we have imposed has been constrained by the cap on the commission's fines".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Darren Grimes representing BeLeave was fined £20,000, the maximum permitted individual fine, for exceeding its spending limit as an unregistered campaigner by more than £660,000 and delivering an inaccurate and incomplete spending return.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Veterans for Britain was also fined £250 for inaccurately reporting a donation it received from Vote Leave.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Electoral Commission referred the matter to the police.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 14 September 2018, following a High Court of Justice case, the court found that Vote Leave had received incorrect advice from the UK Electoral Commission, but confirmed that the overspending had been illegal.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Vote Leave subsequently said they would not have paid it without the advice.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Russian Foreign Ministry spokesperson Maria Zakharova denied these allegations, saying that "Russia is blamed for everything.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Not only in the UK but all over the world.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] (...) But Russia has nothing to do with Brexit at all.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] After the referendum result Putin said that Brexit brought "positives and negatives".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In December 2016, MP Ben Bradshaw speculated in Parliament that Russia may have interfered in the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In February 2017, he called on the GCHQ intelligence service to reveal the information it had on Russian interference.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In April 2017, the House of Commons Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Select Committee (PACAC) issued a report suggesting that there were technical indications that a June 2016 crash of the voter-registration website was caused by a distributed denial-of-service attack using botnets.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The Cabinet Office, in response, stated that it did not believe that "malign intervention" had caused the crash, and instead attributed the crash "to a spike in users just before the registration deadline".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In October 2017, a study by researchers at City, University of London was published in the journal *Social Science Computer Review*.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The article identified 13,493 Twitter accounts that posted a total of about 65,000 messages in the last four weeks of the Brexit referendum campaign, the vast majority campaigning for a "Leave" vote; they were deleted shortly after the referendum.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] A further 26,538 Twitter accounts suddenly changed their username.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The research findings "raised questions about the possibility that a coordinated 'bot army' was deployed, and also about the possibility that Twitter itself may have detected and removed them without disclosing the manipulation".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] In November 2017, the Electoral Commission told *The Times* that it had launched an inquiry to "examine the growing role of social media in election campaigns amid concerns from the intelligence and security agencies that Russia is trying to destabilise the democratic process in Britain".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] The commission was in contact with Facebook and Twitter as part of the inquiry.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] According to Facebook, Russian-based operatives spent 97 cents to place three adverts on the social network in the run-up to the referendum, which were viewed 200 times.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] On 10 June 2018, *The Guardian* reported that investigators from *The Observer* had seen evidence that Leave.EU funder Arron Banks had met Russian officials "multiple times" from 2015 to 2017 and had discussed "a multibillion dollar opportunity to buy Russian goldmines".
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] Three months later, Information Commissioner Elizabeth Denham, who had decided to look into potential unlawful marketing involving repurposing of data during the referendum, produced her final report.
[src:2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum/2016-united-kingdom-european-union-membership-referendum-p03] She concluded that she had found no evidence of Russian involvement in the referendum.
